Swordsmen are melee fighters trained in individual blade mastery through the dueling court tradition of the old city-states, where legal disputes and matters of honor were settled at blade-point under specific rules, witnesses, and documentation requirements. The dueling court was a legal proceeding — a winner received a specific documented legal finding, a loser faced specific consequences distinct from the winner's, and a practitioner who fought exceptionally but lost might achieve a better legal outcome than one who fought poorly but won by luck. Consistency under varied conditions required formal theory, which produced the Cutting Books: codified manuals of blade theory covering timing, measure, and the structures of decision-making that determine whether a specific action achieves its intended effect in contest against varied opponents. The Books were produced by competing schools — lineages of master-to-student transmission organized around particular approaches — whose practitioners' comparative dueling performance drove continuous theoretical development. The tradition's core intellectual formation requires reading the Cutting Books at both the specific level (grounded in observable blade mechanics and timing) and the abstract level (principles that transcend any specific technique or opponent type), enabling practitioners to derive specific responses to any situation from first principles rather than from memorized catalogs. The individual-excellence doctrine — that at the highest levels of blade skill a practitioner can defeat formation-organized opponents by operating in windows between the formation's coordination requirements — stands in institutionalized competitive tension with the Knight tradition's formation-superiority doctrine. The Crusader adept synthesis emerged from the Ash-and-Iron Decades reserve depots where Knight and Swordsman training was forced into the same institutional environment, discovering that chain Knight body-strike mechanics into Swordsman momentum accumulation produces accumulated force beyond what either path sustains alone.

